{
  "text": "From consideration of time-temperature superposition procedures, the temperature measured for T g is expected to show an increase of 5 K to 8 K per tenfold increase of frequency [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] 3 , and there is some evidence of such effects occurring here. The DMTA examined the behavior of the polymer at 1 Hz, and higher frequencies were applied when the effect of temperature on the electrical impedance of the 1-3 piezoelectric composite was examined. For all devices made from each of the materials, maximum loss, occurring in the region of T g , was determined at a higher temperature when examining the electrical impedance of the device than the temperature measured for T g of the polymer using DMTA. Similarly, as a result of the effects of time-temperature superposition, the temperature at which subtle changes in the electrical impedance were recorded are correspondingly higher during assessment of the electrical impedance than those measured at relatively low temperatures using DMTA.",
  "citation_candidates": [
